{
  "answer": "**The famous Ghalib couplet you're referring to is from his ghazal \"Koi ummeed bar nahin aati\" (Diwan-e-Ghalib, Ghazal 115).**\n\n**Urdu transliteration:**  \nMaut ka ek din muayyan hai  \nNeend kyun raat bhar nahin aati[^1]\n\n**English translation:**  \nOne day for death has been decreed;  \nSo why all night does sleep not come to me?[^2]\n\nThis sher (couplet) reflects Ghalib's philosophical meditation on the inevitability of death and the futility of insomnia despite knowing its appointed time.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [p-fda402](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/115-koi-ummeed-bar-nahin-aati/transliteration/#p-fda402).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [p-e23971](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/115-koi-ummeed-bar-nahin-aati/translation/#p-e23971).\n\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [Chapter 115](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/115-koi-ummeed-bar-nahin-aati/translation/).",
